      "content": "{\"claim\": \"A prolonged drought from c.1220–1160 BCE caused widespread aquifer salinization in coastal Mycenaean Greece, Hittite Anatolia, Ugarit and Levantine city‑states, rendering their primary freshwater sources undrinkable and forcing mass abandonment of urban centres.\", \"mechanism\": \"environmental stress (groundwater salinization)\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city‑states\"], \"excludes\": [\"inland settlements\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Sediment cores from coastal wells show no increase in salinity during 1200–1150 BCE\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-geo\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Replaces crop failure with potable water crisis via a different hydrological pathway, maintaining the drought trigger but altering the proximate cause of societal stress.\"}"
